Understate: The claim understates the number of COVID-19 cases linked to the Wisconsin election, as there were 67 people identified who fit the criteria, according to the Wisconsin Department of Health Services.
Lack enough support: The claim lacks enough support as it does not provide any evidence or studies to back up the assertion that there was no statistically significant spike in COVID-19 cases related to the election.
Problematic assumption: The claim makes the problematic assumption that the absence of a "statistically significant spike" in COVID-19 cases directly proves that in-person voting during a pandemic is safe.
Exist alternative explanation: There is an alternative explanation provided by the Texas Tribune CEO, who stated that the Wisconsin Health Department believed at least 36 people got the virus as a consequence of voting in person.
Contradict fact: The claim contradicts the fact that there were cases of COVID-19 linked to the Wisconsin election, as reported by the Wisconsin Department of Health Services.
Falters at times: The claim falters at times by not acknowledging the limitations of the data and the possibility that the identified cases may not have contracted the virus while voting.
Exaggerate: The claim may exaggerate the safety of in-person voting during a pandemic by not fully considering the potential risks and the need for precautions.
